g system)|Android]] and [[iOS (Apple)|iOS]] (iPhone). Handset agnosticism is a major selling point. A handset agnostic system is more attractive to enterprise FMC customers than one that limits the choice of handsets. OptiCaller Software has developed mobile PBX software/apps for most smartphone platforms (Android, iPhone, Blackberry, Windows Mobile and Windows Phone), which also fits to any PBX and Centrex systems.\n\n==Carrier agnostic==\nA system with the mobility controller in the enterprise network can work with any carrier, provided the carrier will allow the phones to connect to their network. The benefit of this is that the customer gets a wide selection of phones, and the FMC system will work on employees\u2019 personal phones, even when those phones are on an assortment of carriers.\n\nA system with the mobility controller in the carrier network is not carrier agnostic from the point of view of the customer. They have to buy service from that carrier.\n\n==PBX agnostic==\nEach of the PBX vendors offers a mobility capability. Some developed it internally. Some, like Cisco or Avaya, bought a third party developer, and some license their offering from a company like OptiCaller Software or Counterpath (formerly FirstHand). There is another set of vendors that offers enterprise FMC that works with any PBX, for example OptiCaller Software, OnRelay, Shortel, Tango Networks, ESCAUX and RIM. This is beneficial to both large and small customers. Large customers may have PBXes from multiple vendors, yet still wish to roll out a unified FMC solution. Small customers appreciate having a choice of supplier, rather than being tied to their PBX vendor.\n\n== Network agnostic interface ==\nSome vendors use this term to mean that all features are available through a uniform user interface in both cellular and Wi-Fi networks. This means that the user should not be able to perceive which network is carrying their session on a dual-mode phone.\n\n== Recent history ==\nFixed\u2013mobile convergence has not developed as expected, allegedly because of lack of demand.<ref>http://www.channelpartnersonline.com/Articles/2010/09/Fixed-Mobile-Convergence-Finding-the-Opportunity.aspx?topic=voice-mail</ref> A paper published by the [[International Telecommunication Union]] (ITU) in 2007 also reaches a pessimistic conclusion.<ref>http://www.itu.int/ITU-D/treg/Events/Seminars/GSR/GSR07/discussion_papers/fixedmobileconvergence.pdf</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Quadruple play]]\n* [[Technological convergence]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fixed-mobile convergence}}\n[[Category:Wi-Fi]]\n[[Category:Computer networking]]\n[[Category:Fixed mobile convergence|*]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through; mos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixed%E2%80%93mobile_convergence"}
{"title_page": "E. R. Bills", "text_new": "'''E. R. Bills''' (born 1967) is an American author and journalist.\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in Fort Worth in 1967, Bills was raised in [[Aledo, Texas]]. His blue-collar parents stressed the importance of a college education and sent him to Europe with the American Institute of Foreign Study at the age of sixteen. \nPursuing studies in art, literature and journalism at [[Texas State University]], Bills garnered numerous state and regional awards for his work as the editor of the university magazine, ''Hillside Scene'' and also served as editor of university\u2019s literary journal, ''Persona''. In 1990, he was a member of Texas State\u2019s national championship-winning team in the [[American Advertising Federation]]'s annual National Student Advertising Competition and graduated from the Texas State University Honors College with a degree in journalism.\n\nBills pursued Master\u2019s courses in American literature at Texas State and the University of Texas at Arlington, but never completed a graduate degree.\n \nIn 2006, Bills became a frequent contributor to ''Fort Worth Weekly''<ref>{{cite web |title=Losing Our (American) Way |url=https://www.fwweekly.com/2006/12/13/losing-our-american-way/ |website=Fort Worth Weekly |accessdate=14 December 2019 |date=13 December 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Oh, for a Reality-based President |url=https://www.fwweekly.com/2007/07/03/oh-for-a-reality-based-president |website=Fort Worth Weekly |accessdate=14 December 2019 |date=3 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Weekly |first1=Fort Worth |title=Foreign Phallacy |url=https://www.fwweekly.com/2009/03/04/foreign-phallacy/ |website=Fort Worth Weekly |accessdate=14 December 2019 |date=4 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Weekly |first1=Fort Worth |title=Johnny Got His Pills |url=https://www.fwweekly.com/2010/10/27/johnny-got-his-pills/ |website=Fort Worth Weekly |accessdate=14 December 2019 |date=27 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Weekly |first1=Fort Worth |title=Whistling Dixie |url=https://www.fwweekly.com/2014/08/20/whistling-dixie/ |website=Fort Worth Weekly |accessdate=14 December 2019 |date=20 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mariani |first1=Anthony |title=The Waco Horror at 100 |url=https://www.fwweekly.com/2016/05/13/the-waco-horror-at-100/ |website=Fort Worth Weekly |accessdate=14 December 2019 |date=13 May 2016}}</ref> and a columnist for the short-lived ''Paper of South Texas''. By 2009, he was writing articles for ''Fort Worth Magazine''<ref>{{cite web |last1=staff |first1=FWTX |title=When Good Ideas Go Bad |url=https://fwtx.com/news/features/good-ideas-go-bad/ |website=Fort Worth Magazine |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en-us |date=5 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=staff |first1=FWTX |title=Great Debate |url=https://fwtx.com/news/features/great-debate/ |website=Fort Worth Magazine |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en-us |date=24 January 2014}}</ref> and served as a community panel columnist for the ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''. Then, he began writing features for newspapers and magazines around the state, including the ''Austin American-Statesman''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bills |first1=E. R. |title=Town's 1910 racial strife a nearly forgotten piece of Texas past |url=http://www.statesman.com/news/opinion/town-1910-racial-strife-nearly-forgotten-piece-texas-past/QiwAMGVKO0YJsnYmzFhv7K/ |website=Austin American-Statesman |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bills |first1=E. R. |title=River's lessons |url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20130602/rivers-lessons |website=Austin American-Statesman |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and ''Texas Co-Op Power'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web |title=To the Bat Cave |url=https://www.texascooppower.com/texas-stories/history/to-the-bat-cave |website=Texas Co-op Power Magazine |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=LagunaMadre |url=https://www.texascooppower.com/travel/gulf-coast/laguna-madre |website=Texas Co-op Power Magazine |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mystery of Spanish Fort |url=https://www.texascooppower.com/texas-stories/history/mystery-of-spanish-fort |website=Texas Co-op Power Magazine |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=East Texas Mojo |url=https://www.texascooppower.com/texas-stories/life-arts/east-texas-mojo |website=Texas Co-op Power Magazine |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref>\nIn early 2013, a feature Bills penned on the 1910 Slocum Massacre (in East Texas) for the ''Austin American-Statesman''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bills |first1=E. R. |title=Town's 1910 racial strife a nearly forgotten piece of Texas past |url=http://www.statesman.com/news/opinion/town-1910-racial-strife-nearly-forgotten-piece-texas-past/QiwAMGVKO0YJsnYmzFhv7K/ |website=Austin American-Statesman |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> caught the attention of The History Press and a commissioning editor subsequently approached him about writing a book. In late 2013, his first book, ''Texas Obscurities: Stories of the Peculiar, Exceptional and Nefarious'' was published by The History Press. In 2014, it was followed by his second title with The History Press, ''The 1910 Slocum Massacre: An Act of Genocide in East Texas''.\nIn 2015, Bills published ''Black Holocaust: The Paris Horror and a Legacy of Texas Terror'' with the Eakin Press. In 2016, Bills took a break from nonfiction and co-edited the Lone Star state\u2019s first anthology of horror, ''Road Kill: Texas Horror by Texas Writers'' (Eakin Press), with fellow Texas author and former schlock filmmaker, Bret McCormick. ''Road Kill: Texas Horror by Texas Writers'' included works from Rio Grande Valley author David Bowles, filmmaker Glen Coburn (creator of the 1984 cult-classic film [[Bloodsuckers from Outer Space]] and legendary Texas author [[Joe R. Lansdale]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Davies |first1=David Martin |title=Texas Matters: Texas Horror |url=https://www.tpr.org/post/texas-matters-texas-horror |website=www.tpr.org |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\nIn August 2017, Eakin Press published Bills\u2019 ''Texas Dissident: Dispatches from a Diminished State, 2006-2016'', a collection of editorials and essays. In early October, the Eakin Press released Bills and McCormick\u2019s ''Road Kill: Texas Horror by Texas Writers, Volume 2''. In mid-October 2017, The History Press released Bills\u2019 fifth book, ''Texas Far and Wide: The Tornado with Eyes, Gettysburg's Last Casualty, the Celestial Skipping Stone and Other Tales''.<ref>{{cite web |title=TEXANA READS: 'Far And Wide' spotlights wide-reaching stories from the Lone Star State |url=https://www.caller.com/story/news/2018/09/15/texana-reads-far-and-wide-tells-texas-stories-wide-appeal/1280449002/ |website=Corpus Christi Caller-Times |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\nIn August 2018, Bills published ''100 Things to Do in Texas Before You Die'' with the Reedy Press<ref>https://www.texasstandard.org/stories/from-isolated-beaches-to-great-tex-mex-get-to-know-100-things-to-do-in-texas-before-you-die/</ref> and was the sole editor of ''Road Kill: Texas Horror by Texas Writers, Volume 3'' (HellBound Books). In October 2019, Bills published ''The San Marcos 10: An Antiwar Protest in Texas'' with The History Press<ref>{{cite web |title=The San Marcos 10 |url=https://www.sanmarcosrecord.com/features/san-marcos-10 |website=San Marcos Record |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en |date=17 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The True History Behind The San Marcos 10 |url=https://yesterdaysamerica.com/the-true-history-behind-the-san-marcos-10/ |website=Yesterday's America |accessdate=14 December 2019 |date=19 November 2019}}</ref> and released his first book of fiction, ''Pendulum Grim'', in December 2019.\nOver the last several years, Bills' historical research and writing has been repeatedly noted by the ''Zinn Education Project'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Genocide in East Texas: A History of the Slocum Massacre |url=https://www.zinnedproject.org/news/slocum-massacre-history/ |website=Zinn Education Project |accessdate=14 December 2019 |date=27 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jan. 28, 1918: Porvenir Massacre |url=https://www.zinnedproject.org/news/tdih/porvenir-massacre/ |website=Zinn Education Project |accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=August 23, 1968: Forty-Three Black Soldiers Stage Sit-In at Ft. Hood |url=https://www.zinnedproject.org/news/tdih/fort-hood-43-sit-in |website=Zinn Education Project |accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref> and his titles have been cited in national publications like ''Smithsonian'' magazine<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boissoneault |first1=Lorraine |title=A Train Company Crashed Two Trains. You Will Believe What Happened Next |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/train-company-crashed-two-trains-you-will-believe-what-happened-next-180964237/ |website=Smithsonian |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and \n[[Mental Floss]] .<ref>{{cite web |title=The Strange Tale of Texas\u2019 All-Female Supreme Court |url=https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/61410/strange-tale-texas-all-female-supreme-court |website=www.mentalfloss.com |accessdate=14 December 2019 |language=en |date=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Slocum Massacre'''\n \nAfter the publication of Bills\u2019 ''The 1910 Slocum Massacre: An Act of Genocide in East Texas'' in May 2014, Bills and Constance Hollie-Jawaid, a descendant of victims of the [[Slocum Massacre]], worked together on a historical marker application commemorating the atrocity. Hollie-Jawaid submitted it to the Anderson County Historical Commission and members there were immediately hostile. Commission officials criticized Hollie-Jawaid\u2019s application, variously claiming it was unprofessional, based on rumors, antagonistic and, finally, too focused on negative history rather than positive.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tilove |first1=Jonathan |title=Slocum Massacre's 'bad history' gains Texas historical marker |url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20160924/slocum-massacres-bad-history-gains-texas-historical-marker |website=Austin American-Statesman |accessdate=16 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Hollie-Jawaid subsequently petitioned the Texas State Historical Commission directly and, on January 29, 2015, the Commission unanimously approved the Slocum Massacre historical marker application with a score of 98 on a 100-point scale.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barajas |first1=Michael |title=It Took Texas a Century to Remember African Americans Slaughtered at Slocum |url=https://www.houstonpress.com/news/it-took-texas-a-century-to-remember-african-americans-slaughtered-at-slocum-8080376 |website=Houston Press |accessdate=16 December 2019 |date=18 January 2016}}</ref><ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/texas-marks-a-racial-slaughter-over-a-100-years-later/2016/01/15/fb194dd0-ba4e-11e5-99f3-184bc379b12d_story.html</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Dillard |first1=Coshandra |title=Slocum Massacre historical marker unveiled |url=https://tylerpaper.com/news/local/slocum-massacre-historical-marker-unveiled/article_4998e176-fe52-5445-ae5a-b4a2ebeee43a.html |website=TylerPaper.com |accessdate=16 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> When it was placed and dedicated on January 16, 2016, it became the first state of Texas historical marker to specifically acknowledge racial violence against African Americans.\nIn 2016, Bills and Hollie-Jawaid completed ''The First Eight'', a screenplay based on the Slocum Massacre. In late 2017, Bills book, ''The 1910 Slocum Massacre: An Act of Genocide in East Texas'', was optioned for film treatment. In early 2018, Bills and Hollie-Jawaid wrote ''Shallow Playground'', a second screenplay related to the Slocum Massacre and it, too, was optioned for film treatment.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shallow Playground |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7528488/ |website=Internet Movie Database |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> \nBills and Hollie-Jawaid continue to work on locating and gaining access to the unmarked mass graves that still contain the remains of victims of the Slocum Massacre.<ref>{{cite web |title=Where the Bodies are Buried |url=https://www.texasobserver.org/where-the-bodies-are-buried/ |website=The Texas Observer |accessdate=16 December 2019 |date=15 July 2019}}</ref> In the October 2019 \n[[Texas Monthly]] cover story, \"The Battle to Rewrite Texas History,\" Bills was mentioned as part of \"a new generation of scholars\" who are attempting to correct the \"historical record\" in the Lone Star state.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Battle to Rewrite Texas History |url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/battle-rewrite-texas-history/ |website=Texas Monthly |accessdate=16 December 2019 |language=en |date=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Nonfiction===\n\n* ''The San Marcos 10: An Antiwar Protest in Texas''. Charleston, SC: The History Press, 2019.\n* ''100 Things to Do in Texas Before You Die''. Saint Louis, Missouri: Reedy Press, 2018.\n* ''Texas Far and Wide: The Tornado with Eyes, Gettysburg's Last Casualty, the Celestial Skipping Stone and Other Tales''. Charleston, SC: The History Press, 2017.\n* ''Texas Dissident: Dispatches from a Diminished State, 2006-2016''. Fort Worth, Texas: Eakin Press, 2017.\n* ''Black Holocaust: The Paris Horror and a Legacy of Texas Terror''. Fort Worth, Texas: Eakin Press, 2015.\n* ''The 1910 Slocum Massacre: An Act of Genocide in East Texas''. Charleston, SC: The History Press, 2014.\n* ''Texas Obscurities: Stories of the Peculiar, Exceptional and Nefarious''. Charleston, SC: The History Press, 2013.\n\n===Fiction===\n\n* ''Pendulum Grim''. IngramSpark, 2019\n\n'''As Editor:'''\n\n* ''Road Kill: Texas Horror by Texas Writers, Vol 3''. Houston, Texas: HellBound Books, 2018.\n* ''Road Kill: Texas Horror by Texas Writers, Vol 2''. Fort Worth, Texas: Eakin Press, 2017.\n* ''Road Kill: Texas Horror by Texas Writers''. Fort Worth, Texas: Eakin Press, 2016.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n*Karen Gavis (2020) \"Hellraisin\u2019: Two Writers Edit and Publish a Yearly Anthology of Texas Horror Stories.\" ''Dallas Observer'', January 31, 2020. https://www.dallasobserver.com/arts/boo-yall-two-authors-collects-texas-horror-tales-11859084\n*Laura Figi (2019). \"San Marcos 10 revisit Texas State for 50-year protest anniversary.\" ''University Star'', November 19, 2019. https://universitystar.com/33040/life_and_arts/san-marcos-10-revisit-texas-state-for-50-year-protest-anniversary/\n*Rachel Sonnier (2019). \"50 Year Anniversary.\" ''San Marcos Daily Record'', November 17, 2019. https://www.sanmarcosrecord.com/features/san-marcos-10\n*[[David Martin Davies]] (2019). \"San Marcos Students' Protest Against Vietnam War Shaped Free Speech On Campuses For 50 Years.\" ''Texas Public Radio''. November 13, 2019. https://www.keranews.org/post/san-marcos-students-protest-against-vietnam-war-shaped-free-speech-campuses-50-years\n*Alvin Sallee (2019). \"'San Marcos 10' explores many experiences during Vietnam War.\" ''The Daily News'' (Galveston County), November 9, 2019. https://www.galvnews.com/books/article_a9effb9a-9512-5aea-96dc-98c906583042.html\n*Christopher Hooks (2019). \u201cThe Battle to Rewrite Texas History.\u201d ''Texas Monthly'', October 2019. https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/battle-rewrite-texas-history/\n*''Book Authority'' (2019). \"25 Best Texas Travel Guide Books of All Time.\"  https://bookauthority.org/books/best-texas-travel-guide-books \n*Michael Barajas (2019). \u201cWhere the Bodies Are Buried. [[Texas Observer]], July 2019. https://www.texasobserver.org/where-the-bodies-are-buried/ \n*Glen Dromgoole (2018). \u201cTexas Reads: Author explores women\u2019s roles in Texas history.\u201d ''A